1 Introduction

In December 2019, a contagious disease (COVID-19) started to spread worldwide leading to the ongoing pandemic. The disease is caused by severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2), which belongs to the family of corona viruses. The first case was identified in Wuhan, China and the virus started spreading quickly (1). The virus spreads from one person to another when they are in close contact through aerosols transmitted from an infected person when they speak, sing, breathe, cough, sneeze (2). However the exact route of transmission is rarely proven (3).

South Korea was one of the first countries to identify the virus outside China, with the first cases being reported in January 2020. The government of South Korea was alert and started to implement measures to restrict the spread of the virus. The measures include, but not restricted to mass testing of population, contact tracing to track and isolate potentially infected persons. The data collected by Korea Centers for Disease Control & Prevention was used to create a structured data set (5).

In this short analysis, the above-mentioned data was used to visualize the spread of the virus and subsequently develop claims regarding the pandemic. For this purpose techniques of data analysis including visualization and statistical testing was conducted using the programming language R.

âData analysis is a process of inspecting, cleansing, transforming and modeling data with the goal of discovering useful informaiton, informing conclusions and supporting decision-making (4).â

This report presents the results of Data analysis conducted on the data from KCDC. It is divided into the following sections. The first section provides an overview of the data along with the code and the second section provides the observations from the statistical analysis.

2.4 Visualisations

Plotting is crucial to data science because: It facilitates making new observations by discovering associations or patterns in data. It facilitates communicating findings. Only relying on summary statistics is dangerous because it reduces data into a single number and carry much less information than a 2D representation. It helps debugging either bugs in the code through visual inspection.

2.4.1 Total Number of Cases

First, the total number of infections were plotted in a time series.

The above plot displays the cumulative number of cases. It does not provide the full picture of the situation that was prevailing in South Korea. Therefore, the cumulative data was converted into incremental and is displayed in the following figure

From the plot, it can be observed that there was a sudden surge in the number of infections in February 2020 and afterwards the number of daily infections dropped. This plot shows that the steps taken by the government was effective in bringing down the daily infections.

2.4.2 Number of Cases per Province

As we have a sight of how the virus spread in time, it is essential for us to understand the number of infections across the different provinces. This representation will provide the information of which provinces were most affected by the pandemic. This representation provides the timeline of the infections in different provinces.

It can be observed that Daegu was the most affected province followed by Seoul. The other provinces have almost equal distribution of cases.

The 5 provinces with the highest number of cases can be observed from the plot. The provinces are 1. Daegu 2. Gyeongsangbuk-do 3. Seoul 4. Gyeonggi-do 5. Incheon

The same plot was performed for the highest number of deaths. It was observed that the number of deaths per province followed the same order as that of the confirmed cases.

2.4.3 Age and Gender

The most frequent speculation during this pandemic was whether age/gender played a role in determining the persons getting infected. In order to visualize this effect the following plots were used. > It can be observed that the gender/age of the person play an important role in getting infected. This claim will be further investigated by a statistical test.

Will this be the case for patient deaths?

To visualise this effect, the number of deaths in each group was plot facetted by the gender in each age group.

When the data is plotted only for gender, it seems that higher number of female patients deceased than the male patients. Sometimes such data can be misleading. A third variable, in this case age, was introduced and data was visualized again

The above plot shows that the number of deceased female patients was higher only in the age group of 80. In other age groups, number of deceased male patients is high.

It also shows that number of deceased patients was higher for the older patients This claim was further investigated using a statistical test

2.4.4 Weather

Another lasting speculation was about the weather and if it had any influence on the number of infections or deaths. The weather includes average temperature, precipitation, wind speed, etc.

From the data, the temporal variation of temperature and the number of cases was visualised.

The above plot shows the temperature and the cumulative caes in South Korea.

This cumulative cases show that temperature does have a correlation with the number of infections. But in reality, this is not the case.

The same plot was repeated for incremental number of cases. It can be observed that temperature does not correlate with the number of infections. This will be supported with a statistical test.

2.4.5 Recovery and Decease Time for patients

Another important factor to be considered in this pandemic is the recovery time of the patients. This adds to the burden on the hospitals. If the patients have a longer recovery time, then the influx of new patients will increase the burden of the hospitals.

It would be helpful to understand the recovery time of different patients and if the recovery time depends on the age/gender of the patients. This claim will be investigated further with a statistical test

Here, the visualization of the data is provided. It is not clear from the above graph if age has any correlation with the average recovery time of the patient. This claim will be further investigated with a statistical test

The same plot was repeated for gender of the patients. It can be inferred that there is no difference between gender and recovery time of patients.

### Major Spreaders As the virus spreads from person to person, it is important to trace the persons who were in contact with an infected person. KCDC also provided trace data and this data was used to determine the type of patients who were spreading the virus.

Do young people spread the virus? or Do male patients spread the virus? How do people spread the virus?

Answering some of the above questions, will help in implementing impactful policies in future.

3 Statistical Test

Statistical tests work by calculating a test statistic â a number that describes how much the relationship between variables in your test differs from the null hypothesis of no relationship.

An important factor to consider when applying a statistical test is to check whether the data on which the test is applied conforms to the assumptions of the test.

In this study, a correlation test is applied to test if one quantitative variable has an effect on the other continuous variable. Hence, a Q-Q plot is used to confirm if the data follows the distribution assumed by the test. For example, the spearmanâs rank correlation test (6) assumes that the data follows a normal distribution.

3.1 Gender and number of cases

To test where there is a correlation between the gender and the number of recorded cases, the wilcoxson test was performed.

Gender is a categorical variable whereas number of recored cases is a quantitative variable and to test a relationship between such two variables, the t-test is preferred. However, to apply the t-test, the distribution of data within the two categorical variable should be normal. In order to test if this assumption holds, a Q-Q plot was used as shown below

qqplot_males <- ggplot(time_gender[sex=="male"],aes(sample=confirmed_d2d)) + 
  stat_qq() + 
  stat_qq_line(col="red",show.legend = T) + 
  xlab("Theorectical Normal distribution") + 
  ylab("Number of confirmed cases") + 
  ggtitle("Q-Q Plot for number of cases among Males") + 
  ThemeMain

qqplot_females <- ggplot(time_gender[sex=="female"],aes(sample=confirmed_d2d)) + 
  stat_qq() + 
  stat_qq_line(col="red",show.legend = T) + 
  xlab("Theorectical Normal distribution") + 
  ylab("Number of confirmed cases") + 
  ggtitle("Q-Q Plot for number of cases among Females") + 
  ThemeMain

qqplot_males + qqplot_females + plot_layout(ncol=2)

It can be observed that although the data follows a normal distribution, there are outliers and because of the presence of outliers, t-test cannot be applied in this case. Hence a wilcoxson test was used.

The null hypothesis was stated as follows: Gender does not play an important role in number of recorded cases.

gender_tst_wilcox <- wilcox.test(data=time_gender,confirmed_d2d~sex)
gender_tst_wilcox$p.value 
## [1] 0.4652327

The P-value was obtained to be 0.46, which is greater than 0.05(our alpha value for determining the validity of null hypothesis). As the P-value is greater than 0.05, the null hypothesis was rejected. Thus, a particular gender is not expected to be affected more.

3.2 Average Recovery Time Vs Age

We have seen from section 2.2 that the recovery time is greater for older people. To test this statistical significance of this observation, a statistical test is performed. The spearmanâs rank correlation test is choosen for this purpose.

Spearmanâs correlation test is a non-parametric measure of rank correlation ((statistical dependence between the rankings of two variables). It assesses how well the relationship between two variables can be described using a monotonic function (6).

This test eliminates the effect of outliers on the correlation. In our data, the average recovery time of age 100 is an outlier because it has only one observation. Therefore, this test is best-suited for this purpose.

decease_dt_age_num <- patients_per_time[,age:=str_replace(age,"s","")][,age:=
                                                                         as.integer(age)]
# statistical testing to support the observation ----------------------------
# H0: the average time for recovery is the same across all age groups
ggplot(patients_per_time[age!=""],aes(as.factor(age),recovery_time))+ 
  geom_boxplot(aes(middle=mean(desease_time))) +
  ggtitle("Age vs Recovery-time") +
  xlab("Age of Patients (years)") + 
  ylab("Time taken to recover (days)")

# Using aov to find correlation between the age group and average time of recovery in each group
recovery_age_aov_new <- patients_per_time[age!="",aov(recovery_time~as.factor(age))]
summary(recovery_age_aov_new) # 2e-16 < 0.005 => reject null
##                  Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## as.factor(age)   10  16736  1673.6   10.41 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals      1565 251567   160.7                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 2209 observations deleted due to missingness
# convert age into num and find the correlation 
recovery_age_cor_new <- decease_dt_age_num[,cor.test(age,recovery_time,method="spearman")]

ggplot(decease_dt_age_num,aes(age,recovery_time)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  stat_smooth(method = lm) + 
  geom_label(x=10,y=90,label=paste("Spearman=",round(recovery_age_cor_new$estimate,2))) +
  ggtitle("Correlation between age and recovery time of patient") +
  xlab("Age of patients") + 
  ylab("Time taken to recover (days)") + 
  ThemeMain
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

The correlation coefficient is 0.16. It shows that there is a small positive correlation between recovery time of patients. However, this coefficient is low and it is not enough to conclude this observation. More data is required.

3.3 Average Decease Time Vs Age

The same statistical test was conducted to verify the correlation between the age of the patient and decease time.

decease_age_cor_new <- decease_dt_age_num[,cor.test(age,desease_time,method="spearman")]

ggplot(decease_dt_age_num,aes(age,desease_time)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  stat_smooth(method = lm) + 
  geom_label(x=60,y=50,label=paste("Spearman=",round(decease_age_cor_new$estimate,2))) +
  ggtitle("Correlation between age and decease time of patient") +
  xlab("Age of patients") + 
  ylab("Time between disease-confirmation and decease")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

The correlation coefficient is 0.27, which signifies a stronger correlation with age compared to the recovery time.

3.4 Number of Deceased Vs Age

The spearman correlation test performed between age and number of deceased cases revealed that there is a strong positive correlation between them. However, in this study the exact age of the patient is not know. Only the number of cases in a particular age group is known. With this information, there seems to be a positive correlation but more information is needed to confirm this observation.

# correlation test ----------------------------------------------------------
# age vs total number of confirmed cases and number of deaths
time_age_num <- time_age %>% mutate(str_replace(time_age$age,"s",""))
time_age_num <-time_age_num[,age:=NULL]
sn <- names(time_age_num)[1:6]
names(time_age_num) <- c(sn,"age")
time_age_num <- time_age_num[,age:=as.numeric(age)]


time_age_num <- time_age_num[,tot_confirmed:=sum(confirmed_d2d),by=.(age)]
time_age_num <- time_age_num[,tot_deceased:=sum(deceased_d2d),by=.(age)]


time_age_num_cor_dt <- time_age_num[1:9,.(age,tot_confirmed,tot_deceased)]

age_num_cor <- time_age_num_cor_dt[,cor.test(age,tot_confirmed,method = "spearman")]

age_num_cor_de <- time_age_num_cor_dt[,cor.test(age,tot_deceased,method = "spearman")]
## Warning in cor.test.default(age, tot_deceased, method = "spearman"): Cannot

  geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = lm) +

3.5 Impact of Weather on the spread of Covid-19

When the pandemic first started, there was a wide speculation about the role of weather on the spread of the virus. Therefore, with the available data, the relationship between weather params such as average temperature, maximum temperature, maximum temperature and precipitation was tested in this study.

To keep the report length in check, only the correaltion between average temperature and number of confirmed cases is presented in this report.

time_province_covid_weather <- time_province_dt[province!="Sejong"][date != as.Date("2020-06-30")]
time_province_covid_weather <- time_province_covid_weather[,`:=`(confirmed_d2d=c(confirmed[1],diff(confirmed)),
                                                                 released_d2d=c(released[1],diff(released)),
                                                                 deceased_d2d = c(deceased[1],diff(deceased))),
                                                           by=.(province)]

weather_2020_dt <- weather_dt[date >= as.Date("2020-01-20")]

# merge weather and province data
#rm(weather_covid_province_dt)
weather_covid_province_dt <- merge(weather_2020_dt,time_province_covid_weather,by=c("date","province"),all=T)

avgTemp_confirmed_cor <- weather_covid_province_dt[,cor.test(avg_temp,confirmed_d2d,method="spearman")]

ggplot(weather_covid_province_dt,aes(confirmed_d2d,avg_temp)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method=lm) + 
  geom_label(x=5,y=5,label=paste("Spearman=",round(avgTemp_confirmed_cor$estimate,2)))+ 
  xlab("Number of Confirmed Cases") + 
  ylab("Average Temperature (Â°C)") + 
  ggtitle("Correlation between Average Temperature and the Number of infections") +
  ThemeMain
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

There is no significant correlation between average temperature and the number of confirmed cases. The same behaviour was observed for other weather parameters
